<br>
As a preface, I’ll tell you that I mainly play a level 60 enchanter, although it wasn’t my first character.  So while I’ll have some basis to talk to you as an enchanter, I didn’t play the early levels at the same time I was learning how to play the game in general.<br>
<br>
Almost everybody in the game has gone through what you’re going through, especially regarding money.  At low levels it’s almost impossible to earn enough to not feel worried about how you will buy your next set of spells.  I remember feeling like you do, that I just couldn’t imagine having 100 pp let alone the thousands that people were paying for items.  I will say that it gets better, but not until much later in the game.  I think I was level 35-40 before money started becoming less of an issue, although it never goes away entirely for most of us.<br>
<br>
And as to those people you see with awesome gear and lots of money at lower levels, be assured that they didn’t obtain that gear &amp; money with the low level character.  Many people, myself included, buy gear with money we earned with our higher level characters and give it to our lower level characters.  It’s called twinking.  Some people think it’s bad to do it, but it’s a very common practice.<br>
<br>
As for buying your next spells, two possible options for you would be to kill skeletons for bone chips and try to sell them to players, or to repeatedly deliver mail from felwith to kelethin.  Both options are boring, but they would eventually let you get your spells.<br>
<br>
As for grouping, I also remember being very reluctant to group.  My very first character was a ranger, and I was almost lvl 10 before I ever got in a group.  It was a disaster.  But grouping, especially for an enchanter, is almost essential, especially as you increase in level.  Enchanters don’t specialize in doing things directly.  They don’t fight well.  They don’t nuke well.  Their pets are of limited value.  They can’t heal. What then can do, however, is affect their environment, and they do that well.  One of the keys to being a successful enchanter is making sure you have plenty of environment to affect.  one orc + you doesn’t leave you very much to affect, but several orcs + five group members + you gives you a lot to work with.  Basically, I’m saying that enchanters are poor soloers, although it can be done at lower levels, but awesome in groups.  But learning to be an effective group is harder then learning how to solo.  Just make sure that the loot is being shared fairly.<br>
<br>
Feel free to send me a tell in game if you have specific questions. <br>
<br>
